### Resource Selection

OpenMaui supports **density-qualified resources** similar to Android's drawable-mdpi/hdpi/xhdpi system:

```
Resources/
  Images/
    logo.png          # 1× baseline (96 DPI)
    logo@1.5x.png     # 1.5× (144 DPI)
    logo@2x.png       # 2× (192 DPI)
    logo@3x.png       # 3× (288 DPI)
```

The image handler automatically selects the appropriate resource:

```csharp
public class SkiaImage : SkiaView
{
    private SKBitmap LoadImageWithDensity(string imagePath, double dpi)
    {
        var scaleFactor = dpi / 96.0;

        // Try to find density-qualified resource
        var qualifiedPath = FindDensityQualifiedResource(
            imagePath, scaleFactor);

        var bitmap = SKBitmap.Decode(qualifiedPath);

        // Adjust bitmap density metadata
        bitmap.SetImmutable();

        return bitmap;
    }

    private string FindDensityQualifiedResource(
        string basePath, double targetScale)
    {
        var directory = Path.GetDirectoryName(basePath);
        var filename = Path.GetFileNameWithoutExtension(basePath);
        var extension = Path.GetExtension(basePath);

        // Define scale qualifiers in preference order
        var qualifiers = new[] { "@3x", "@2x", "@1.5x" };
        var thresholds = new[] { 2.5, 1.75, 1.25 };

        for (int i = 0; i < qualifiers.Length; i++)
        {
            if (targetScale >= thresholds[i])
            {
                var qualifiedPath = Path.Combine(directory,
                    $"{filename}{qualifiers[i]}{extension}");

                if (File.Exists(qualifiedPath))
                    return qualifiedPath;
            }
        }

        return basePath; // Fall back to baseline resource
    }
}
```

### Vector Graphics

For truly resolution-independent graphics, OpenMaui supports **SVG rendering** via Svg.Skia:

```csharp
public class SkiaImage : SkiaView
{
    private void RenderSvg(SKCanvas canvas, string svgPath, SKRect bounds)
    {
        var svg = new SKSvg();
        svg.Load(svgPath);

        // SVG renders at any scale without quality loss
        var scale = Math.Min(
            bounds.Width / svg.Picture.CullRect.Width,
            bounds.Height / svg.Picture.CullRect.Height);

        canvas.Save();
        canvas.Translate(bounds.Left, bounds.Top);
        canvas.Scale(scale);
        canvas.DrawPicture(svg.Picture);
        canvas.Restore();
    }
}
```

SVG icons and graphics scale perfectly to any DPI without requiring multiple asset versions, making them ideal for toolbar icons, app logos, and decorative elements.

### Font Scaling

OpenMaui's text rendering respects both DPI scaling and user-configured font sizes:

```csharp
public class SkiaLabel : SkiaView
{
    protected override void OnDraw(SKCanvas canvas)
    {
        var paint = new SKPaint
        {
            Typeface = GetTypeface(),
            TextSize = (float)(FontSize * _dpiScale * _userFontScale),
            IsAntialias = true,
            SubpixelText = true
        };

        // HarfBuzz shapes text at final size
        var shapedText = ShapeText(Text, paint);
        canvas.DrawShapedText(shapedText, 0, 0, paint);
    }

    private double GetUserFontScale()
    {
        // Query desktop environment font scaling
        if (IsGnome())
        {
            return GSettings.GetDouble(
                "org.gnome.desktop.interface", 
                "text-scaling-factor");
        }

        return 1.0;
    }
}
```

This ensures text remains readable for users who configure larger system fonts for accessibility.

